performance_optimizations.description:
The orders table scan (353.7ms, 53% of total) is I/O bound on HDD. Current code uses madvise(MADV_SEQUENTIAL) but doesn't prefetch qualifying blocks identified by zone map analysis.

Specific changes to q3.cpp:
1. After identifying qualifying_blocks (lines 205-211), calculate the memory ranges to prefetch
2. Use madvise(MADV_WILLNEED) on all 4 orders columns for qualifying blocks BEFORE starting parallel scan threads
3. Add prefetch for lineitem columns (l_orderkey, l_extendedprice, l_discount, l_shipdate) using the same technique
4. Consider using MAP_POPULATE flag during mmap for hot columns (o_orderdate, l_shipdate) to fault in pages immediately

Code pattern:
```cpp
// After line 211 (qualifying_blocks identified)
for (size_t block_id : qualifying_blocks) {
    size_t start_row = block_id * block_size;
    size_t end_row = std::min(start_row + block_size, orders_row_count);
    size_t byte_start = start_row * sizeof(int32_t);
    size_t byte_count = (end_row - start_row) * sizeof(int32_t);
    madvise((void*)(o_orderkey + start_row), byte_count, MADV_WILLNEED);
    madvise((void*)(o_custkey + start_row), byte_count, MADV_WILLNEED);
    // ... repeat for o_orderdate, o_shippriority
}
```

Expected improvement: On HDD with 100MB/s sequential read, prefetching can hide 50-70% of I/O latency by parallelizing disk seeks with computation. Estimate: 353.7ms → 150-200ms (1.8-2.4x speedup on orders scan). Reference: storage/persistent-storage.md recommends MADV_WILLNEED for predictable access patterns.

The orders scan loop (lines 228-232) performs sequential date comparisons (o_orderdate[i] < date_1995_03_15). This is a vectorizable operation that can process 8 int32 comparisons per instruction using AVX2 (hardware supports avx2 and avx512f).

Specific changes to q3.cpp:
1. Add #include <immintrin.h> at top
2. Inside the thread lambda (lines 228-232), replace scalar loop with SIMD batching:

```cpp
const __m256i threshold = _mm256_set1_epi32(date_1995_03_15);
size_t i = start_row;
for (; i + 8 <= end_row; i += 8) {
    __m256i dates = _mm256_loadu_si256((__m256i*)(o_orderdate + i));
    __m256i cmp = _mm256_cmpgt_epi32(threshold, dates); // dates < threshold
    int mask = _mm256_movemask_ps(_mm256_castsi256_ps(cmp));

    // Process matching lanes
    for (int lane = 0; lane < 8; ++lane) {
        if (mask & (1 << lane)) {
            if (building_custkeys.count(o_custkey[i + lane]) > 0) {
                local_map[o_orderkey[i + lane]] = {o_orderdate[i + lane], o_shippriority[i + lane]};
            }
        }
    }
}
// Scalar tail
for (; i < end_row; ++i) { /* original loop */ }
```

3. Apply same pattern to lineitem scan (line 292: l_shipdate[i] > date_1995_03_15)

Expected improvement: Date filtering is ~10-15% of scan CPU time. SIMD can reduce this by 4-6x (processing 8 values per instruction). Estimate: 15-20ms savings in orders scan, 10-15ms in lineitem. Reference: parallelism/simd.md shows vectorized comparison produces bitmasks for efficient filtering.

The revenue calculation (line 309: l_extendedprice[i] * (1.0 - l_discount[i])) is performed sequentially for ~3-4M qualifying lineitem rows. This is vectorizable using AVX2/AVX-512 to process 4-8 double-precision values per instruction.

Specific changes to q3.cpp:
1. Inside the lineitem scan thread lambda (lines 290-317), batch revenue calculations:

```cpp
// After passing all filters and finding match in qualified_orders
std::vector<size_t> matching_indices;
matching_indices.reserve(1024);

// Collect matching row indices in batches
for (size_t i = start; i < end; ++i) {
    if (l_shipdate[i] <= date_1995_03_15) continue;
    auto it = qualified_orders.find(l_orderkey[i]);
    if (it == qualified_orders.end()) continue;
    matching_indices.push_back(i);

    // Process batch of 8 when full
    if (matching_indices.size() >= 8) {
        __m256d ones = _mm256_set1_pd(1.0);
        for (size_t j = 0; j + 4 <= matching_indices.size(); j += 4) {
            __m256d prices = _mm256_loadu_pd(&l_extendedprice[matching_indices[j]]);
            __m256d discounts = _mm256_loadu_pd(&l_discount[matching_indices[j]]);
            __m256d revenues = _mm256_mul_pd(prices, _mm256_sub_pd(ones, discounts));
            // Store and aggregate revenues...
        }
        matching_indices.clear();
    }
}
```

Note: This requires gathering scattered indices, which may reduce SIMD efficiency. Alternative: Use branch-free masking to compute revenue for all rows and conditionally aggregate.

Expected improvement: Revenue calculation is ~5-10% of join_aggregation time (~8-15ms). SIMD can reduce by 2-3x (4 doubles per AVX2 instruction). Savings: 5-10ms. Reference: parallelism/simd.md recommends horizontal aggregation in SIMD registers.

The lineitem table is sorted by l_shipdate (storage design line 31), and a zone map index exists (storage design line 35), but the current code does NOT use it. The query filters l_shipdate > 1995-03-15 (selectivity ~54%, filtering out 46% of rows), so zone maps could skip ~275 of 600 blocks.

Specific changes to q3.cpp:
1. After line 273 (mmap lineitem columns), load the l_shipdate zone map:
```cpp
size_t lineitem_zonemap_size;
const void* lineitem_zonemap_data = mmapFile(gendb_dir + "/lineitem/l_shipdate.zonemap.idx", lineitem_zonemap_size);
const uint64_t* lineitem_num_blocks_ptr = (const uint64_t*)lineitem_zonemap_data;
const size_t lineitem_num_blocks = *lineitem_num_blocks_ptr;
const ZoneMapBlock* lineitem_zone_blocks = (const ZoneMapBlock*)((const char*)lineitem_zonemap_data + 8);
```

2. Identify qualifying lineitem blocks (before line 277):
```cpp
std::vector<size_t> lineitem_qualifying_blocks;
for (size_t b = 0; b < lineitem_num_blocks; ++b) {
    if (lineitem_zone_blocks[b].max_value > date_1995_03_15) {
        lineitem_qualifying_blocks.push_back(b);
    }
}
```

3. Modify parallel scan (lines 282-319) to iterate over lineitem_qualifying_blocks instead of full chunk_size ranges:
```cpp
for (size_t t = 0; t < num_threads; ++t) {
    threads.emplace_back([&, t]() {
        for (size_t idx = t; idx < lineitem_qualifying_blocks.size(); idx += num_threads) {
            size_t block_id = lineitem_qualifying_blocks[idx];
            size_t start_row = block_id * block_size;
            size_t end_row = std::min(start_row + block_size, lineitem_row_count);
            // ... scan loop ...
        }
    });
}
```

Expected improvement: Skip ~275 of 600 blocks (46% of lineitem). Each skipped block saves ~0.25ms I/O + CPU (rough estimate). Savings: 70-100ms on join_aggregation phase. Reference: indexing/zone-maps.md shows block skipping is highly effective on sorted data with range predicates.

The merge phase (lines 330-346) sequentially merges local aggregation maps into a global map (38.8ms, 6% of total). For 64 threads with ~1000-5000 groups each, this involves ~64K-320K hash insertions/updates performed single-threaded.

Specific changes to q3.cpp:
1. Replace sequential merge with parallel tree reduction:
```cpp
// After line 328 (join threads complete)
auto t_merge_start = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();

// Tree reduction: merge pairs of local_maps in parallel
std::vector<absl::flat_hash_map<AggregateKey, AggregateValue>> current_level = std::move(local_maps);
while (current_level.size() > 1) {
    std::vector<absl::flat_hash_map<AggregateKey, AggregateValue>> next_level;
    size_t num_pairs = (current_level.size() + 1) / 2;
    next_level.resize(num_pairs);

    std::vector<std::thread> merge_threads;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < num_pairs; ++i) {
        merge_threads.emplace_back([&, i]() {
            size_t left_idx = i * 2;
            size_t right_idx = i * 2 + 1;
            next_level[i] = std::move(current_level[left_idx]);
            if (right_idx < current_level.size()) {
                for (const auto& entry : current_level[right_idx]) {
                    auto it = next_level[i].find(entry.first);
                    if (it == next_level[i].end()) {
                        next_level[i][entry.first] = entry.second;
                    } else {
                        it->second.revenue += entry.second.revenue;
                    }
                }
            }
        });
    }
    for (auto& t : merge_threads) t.join();
    current_level = std::move(next_level);
}
absl::flat_hash_map<AggregateKey, AggregateValue> global_map = std::move(current_level[0]);
```

2. This reduces merge depth from O(n) to O(log n) and parallelizes each merge level.

Expected improvement: Current merge is 38.8ms single-threaded. Parallel tree reduction with 64 threads: ~6-10ms (4-6x speedup). Savings: 30-35ms. Reference: aggregation/partial-aggregation.md recommends parallel merge for multi-threaded aggregation.
